        content: "Judges communicate constantly through their body even when they're silent:\n\n**Positive Signals (They Like What You're Saying):**\n• Nodding while you speak — they agree or follow your reasoning\n• Leaning forward — they're engaged and interested\n• Sustained eye contact — they're focused on you\n• Writing actively — they're flowing your arguments (good sign)\n• Slight smile or raised eyebrows — your point landed well\n\n**Negative Signals (They're Not Buying It):**\n• Furrowed brow or squinting — they're confused or skeptical\n• Leaning back with crossed arms — they're disengaged or resistant\n• Looking at the clock frequently — they want you to move on\n• Stopped writing — they've stopped flowing, meaning they don't think it matters\n• Shaking head subtly — they disagree with your point\n\n**Neutral/Ambiguous Signals:**\n• Blank expression — could mean anything; they may be focusing internally\n• Looking at evidence — they're processing, not necessarily agreeing or disagreeing\n• Shifting in seat — could be discomfort or restlessness, not necessarily about your argument\n\n**Important Caveats:**\n• Some judges are deliberately expressionless to avoid influencing the round\n• Cultural differences affect body language interpretation\n• Don't over-read a single gesture — look for patterns over time\n• Focus on clusters of signals rather than individual movements",
