        content: "How and when a judge writes tells you a lot about what they value:\n\n**Heavy Note-Takers:**\n• They flow everything — this usually means they're a technical, flow-based judge\n• They'll compare arguments point-by-point in their decision\n• Make sure you're clear and organized so they can follow your flow\n• Sign-posting becomes critical: 'On their second contention...'\n\n**Selective Note-Takers:**\n• They write down certain things and skip others\n• Watch what makes them pick up the pen — that's what they care about\n• If they write during your impact analysis but not your evidence reading, they prioritize impacts over evidence\n• If they write during cross-ex, they value clash moments\n\n**Minimal Note-Takers:**\n• They rely on overall impression rather than detailed flow\n• Big-picture arguments and clear narratives matter more than technical details\n• These judges often care more about persuasion and storytelling\n• Repetition of key themes helps because they're not tracking everything\n\n**What to Watch For:**\n• When the pen starts moving — what triggered it?\n• When the pen stops — what lost their interest?\n• Do they write more during constructives or rebuttals?\n• Do they take notes during cross-examination?\n\n**Using This Information:**\nIf you notice the judge writes more when you discuss real-world impacts, spend more time there. If they write during evidence citations, emphasize your sourcing. Match your emphasis to their attention.",
