        content: "Judges sometimes speak during the round, and these moments are gold mines of information:\n\n**During Cross-Examination:**\n• If a judge leans in during a cross-ex exchange, that issue matters to them\n• If they ask their own clarifying question (in formats where this is allowed), they're interested in that argument\n• If they say 'Can you repeat that?', they want to flow it — it's important to them\n\n**Point of Information/Clarification:**\n• Some judges ask for clarification on evidence or arguments\n• What they ask about reveals what they're weighing\n• A judge who asks about your impact numbers cares about quantitative evidence\n• A judge who asks about your framework cares about the decision lens\n\n**Post-Round Oral Critique:**\n• Even though this comes after the decision, it's invaluable for future rounds\n• Listen for phrases like 'What I was looking for was...' or 'What would have won you this round is...'\n• Take notes on their feedback\n• Apply it if you face them again\n\n**Tone and Speed of Questions:**\n• Skeptical tone when asking about an argument = they doubt it\n• Genuinely curious tone = they're interested and open\n• Quick, pointed questions = they want specific information\n• Open-ended questions = they want you to develop the argument further\n\n**Strategic Application:**\nWhen a judge signals interest in an argument — verbally or nonverbally — invest more time there in your rebuttals. When they signal disinterest or skepticism, either address their concern directly or pivot to stronger ground.",
