        content: "Some of the best information comes from watching the judge while your opponent speaks:\n\n**Why This Matters:**\nYou can see which opponent arguments land well and which fall flat — before you have to respond to them. This is a huge strategic advantage.\n\n**What to Watch:**\n\n**Judge Engagement Level:**\n• Are they writing vigorously? The opponent is making strong points you need to answer.\n• Are they looking bored or distracted? Those arguments may not need heavy rebuttal.\n• Are they nodding? The judge finds these arguments persuasive.\n\n**Judge Reactions to Specific Arguments:**\n• Skeptical expression during an argument = opportunity for you to exploit that skepticism\n• Strong engagement with an argument = you must address it thoroughly\n• Confusion during an argument = you might be able to point out the confusion and capitalize\n\n**During Opponent's Cross-Ex of You:**\n• Watch if the judge seems to think a question is fair or unfair\n• Notice if the judge seems satisfied with your answer or not\n• If the judge nods when you answer, your response landed\n\n**Building Your Rebuttal Strategy:**\nUse what you observe to prioritize:\n1. Spend the most time on opponent arguments the judge seemed to find persuasive\n2. Spend less time on arguments the judge seemed skeptical of\n3. Exploit moments of judge confusion about opponent positions\n4. Reference moments that clearly resonated: 'As we discussed earlier...'",
