        content: "Reading judges is a skill that improves with deliberate practice:\n\n**Practice Techniques:**\n\n**1. The 30-Second Check-In:**\nEvery 30 seconds during a speech, briefly glance at the judge. Don't stare — just a quick look to read their current state. Over time, this becomes automatic.\n\n**2. The Cross-Ex Observation Window:**\nCross-examination is the easiest time to watch the judge because you're not speaking continuously. Use these moments to read their reactions to the exchange.\n\n**3. Post-Round Journaling:**\nAfter each round, write down what you observed about the judge's behavior and whether your read was accurate based on the decision. This builds pattern recognition.\n\n**4. Practice Rounds:**\nIn practice, have someone watch the judge for you and compare notes. This calibrates your observation skills.\n\n**Common Mistakes:**\n• Staring at the judge instead of making natural eye contact\n• Letting judge reactions distract you from your speech\n• Over-interpreting a single gesture\n• Changing your entire strategy based on one head shake\n• Ignoring the judge entirely and reading from your notes\n\n**Balance Is Key:**\nYou need to observe the judge while still delivering a strong speech. This takes practice. Start by making brief check-ins and gradually increase your awareness without sacrificing delivery quality.",
