        content: "Speed is the most immediate adaptation you can make:\n\n**For Speed-Tolerant Judges (Experienced Flow Judges):**\n• You can speak at a fast pace, but maintain clarity\n• Slow down slightly on taglines, author names, and key claims\n• Use clear sign-posting so they can keep up on their flow: 'Next, on Contention 2, subpoint B...'\n• Speed is a tool — use it to cover more ground, not to overwhelm\n\n**For Moderate-Speed Judges:**\n• Target 150-180 words per minute — fast enough to cover ground, slow enough to follow\n• Pause between arguments to let them write\n• Watch their pen — if they're still writing, slow down\n• Use transitional phrases to signal new arguments\n\n**For Slow-Pace Judges (Lay Judges, Parent Volunteers):**\n• Speak conversationally — 120-140 words per minute\n• Use natural pauses for emphasis\n• Repeat key points in different words\n• Don't try to fit too many arguments in — fewer, better-developed arguments win\n\n**Dynamic Pacing:**\nThe best debaters don't maintain one speed throughout. They accelerate through less important material and slow down for crucial arguments. This creates natural emphasis:\n• Fast: Background information, less contested points\n• Slow: Key arguments, impact analysis, voting issues\n• Pause: Before and after your most important claims\n\n**Reading the Room:**\nIf you see the judge struggling to keep up — pen racing, confused expression — slow down immediately. No argument is worth making if the judge can't process it.",
