        content: "Tone and energy convey confidence, urgency, and credibility — but different judges respond to different tones:\n\n**For Serious, Academic Judges:**\n• Professional, measured tone — think professor, not preacher\n• Controlled energy that conveys competence\n• Avoid excessive emotion or dramatic flourishes\n• Let your reasoning speak rather than your volume\n• Use precise language and defined terms\n\n**For Persuasion-Oriented Judges:**\n• Vary your tone to create emotional arcs\n• Build energy toward key moments\n• Use strategic pauses for dramatic effect\n• Show genuine passion for your position\n• Tell stories and paint pictures\n• Your conviction matters — they want to feel your belief in your argument\n\n**For Technical Flow Judges:**\n• Clear, steady, even tone — think newsreader\n• Energy should be focused, not scattered\n• Monotone is okay if it means clarity\n• Emphasize structure over flair\n• Sound organized and in control\n\n**For Lay/Community Judges:**\n• Warm, conversational, approachable tone\n• Moderate energy — engaged but not overwhelming\n• Smile naturally\n• Sound like a smart person explaining something interesting, not a competitor attacking\n• Avoid sounding aggressive or condescending\n\n**Universal Principles:**\n• Confidence matters for every judge type — never sound uncertain about your own arguments\n• Match the judge's energy level as a baseline, then adjust\n• Authenticity wins — forced enthusiasm is worse than calm confidence",
