        title: "Argument Selection for Evidence Judges",
        content: "When you know your judge prioritizes evidence quality, restructure your argument priorities:\n\n**Lead With:**\n• Arguments supported by your strongest evidence cards\n• Claims backed by peer-reviewed research or expert testimony\n• Quantitative data and specific statistics\n• Arguments where you have multiple supporting sources\n\n**Minimize or Avoid:**\n• Logical arguments without evidence support\n• Analytical arguments based on reasoning alone\n• Arguments where your evidence is weak or outdated\n• Common-sense claims that feel intuitive but lack sourcing\n\n**Evidence Comparison Strategy:**\n• Build your case around 2-3 heavily evidenced arguments rather than 5-6 lightly supported ones\n• Prepare to win the evidence comparison on your best arguments\n• Know your sources deeply — author background, methodology, publication context\n• Have backup evidence ready if primary evidence is challenged\n\n**Practical Example:**\nSuppose your case has three contentions: one with excellent evidence, one with moderate evidence, and one based primarily on logical reasoning. Before an evidence judge:\n• Spend 40% of your time on the strong-evidence contention\n• Spend 35% on the moderate-evidence contention (bolstering the sourcing)\n• Spend 25% on the logic contention (acknowledge limitations, connect to evidence)\n\n**The Key Shift:**\nYou're not dropping arguments — you're changing emphasis. The logic-based contention still matters, but you lead with evidence strength and let that set the tone for your case.",
