        content: "Logic judges want clear reasoning chains. Adapt your arguments accordingly:\n\n**Lead With:**\n• Arguments with the clearest causal chain: If A, then B, then C\n• Arguments where you can explain the mechanism step by step\n• Arguments that are internally consistent and don't contradict each other\n• Framework arguments that set logical criteria for the round\n\n**Minimize or Avoid:**\n• Arguments that rely heavily on evidence authority without explaining why\n• Arguments with logical gaps you can't fill\n• Arguments that create internal contradictions with your other positions\n• Emotional appeals without logical foundation\n\n**Strengthen Your Logic:**\n• For every claim, ask 'Why?' and make sure you have an answer\n• For every answer, ask 'Why?' again — go at least three levels deep\n• Anticipate the logical objections and address them preemptively\n• Build explicit connections between arguments\n\n**Weighing for Logic Judges:**\nLogic judges love explicit impact calculus:\n• 'Our argument outweighs because of magnitude — we prevent X while they prevent Y'\n• 'Our argument is more probable — their scenario requires five unlikely steps while ours requires one'\n• 'Even under their framework, our argument wins because...'\n\n**Practical Example:**\nIf you have a strong emotional argument about suffering and a structural argument about systemic incentives, lead with the structural argument. Present the suffering argument as evidence for the structural claim rather than as a standalone emotional appeal. Reframe: 'The suffering we describe is the predictable result of the structural problem, which is why the structural fix is essential.'",
