        content: "Flow judges track every argument and expect you to respond to every argument. Strategy here is about coverage and execution:\n\n**Lead With:**\n• Responses to every opponent argument (don't drop anything on the flow)\n• Clear extensions of your own arguments with added analysis\n• Technical concessions and turns (these impress flow judges)\n• Organized responses numbered clearly: 'Three responses to their DA...'\n\n**Emphasize:**\n• Argument interaction — how your arguments interact with theirs\n• Drops — if opponent drops an argument, extend it and explain why it matters\n• Turns — show how opponent arguments actually support your position\n• Weighing — explicit comparison of argument strength on the flow\n\n**Minimize:**\n• New emotional appeals in rebuttals\n• Repetition of arguments already on the flow\n• General statements that don't attach to specific flow positions\n• Vague impact claims without connection to specific arguments\n\n**Strategic Depth:**\nFlow judges reward debaters who show technical mastery:\n• 'They dropped our third response on their contention 1 — this argument alone is sufficient to take out their entire case because...'\n• 'Cross-apply our evidence from contention 2 to answer their disadvantage link — the same data shows...'\n• 'Group their arguments 2 and 3 — they make the same fundamental error...'\n\n**The Flow Judge Mindset:**\nFlow judges see the debate as a spreadsheet. Each argument lives in a cell. They look at which cells were won, which were dropped, and how the interaction plays out. Make their job easy by being organized, thorough, and precise.",
